, I share facts in a calm, non‑judgmental tone. I rely on reputable sources such as the World Health Organization and local health authorities, but I frame the information in everyday language: “The vaccine is like a shield; it doesn’t change who you are.” By keeping the conversation grounded in familiar metaphors, I avoid alienating those who might feel overwhelmed by scientific jargon. Third, I set boundaries. If a discussion turns into an argument or if someone becomes hostile, I politely steer the conversation back to the salon’s purpose: ensuring everyone feels safe and comfortable. I remind them that my priority is their well‑being, not to convince them of any particular stance. Finally, I model self‑care. I get vaccinated myself, but I also encourage clients to consult with their doctors, especially if they have underlying conditions. By sharing my own experience—how the vaccine helped me avoid illness—I provide a personal example without imposing it on others.

